# ADR-0001: Record architecture decisions
Status: accepted
Date: {{DATE}}
Supersedes: —
Superseded by: —

## Context

We make architectural choices throughout the life of this project — frameworks,
data models, boundaries, dependencies. These choices shape every subsequent
change, but their rationale is usually lost: it lives in chat history, in
people's heads, in PR threads that nobody re-reads.

We need a small, durable record that future maintainers (and our future selves)
can rely on.

## Decision

We will record architecture decisions as **Architecture Decision Records
(ADRs)** in `docs/adr/`, following Michael Nygard's lightweight format.

- One file per decision, numbered monotonically: `NNNN-slug.md`.
- Each ADR carries: Context, Decision, Consequences, Alternatives, Verification.
- Status lifecycle: `proposed → accepted → superseded | deprecated`.
- ADRs are **append-only**: past records are not edited; a changed decision
  produces a new ADR that supersedes the old one (only the status pointer on
  the old record may be updated).

New ADRs are proposed automatically during plan close-out (the `/plan`
command's Phase 4 decides per a confidence rule). For ad-hoc decisions
outside a plan, copy `_template.md` to `NNNN-slug.md` with status
`proposed`.

## Consequences

- ✅ Decisions are durable and reviewable in PRs alongside the code they affect.
- ✅ "Why is it this way?" has a citable answer.
- ⚠️ Adds a small ceremony: significant decisions cost ~10 minutes to record.
  We accept this — the cost of forgotten rationale is higher.
- 🔒 We rule out informal-only decisions: any architectural change that a
  reviewer can't trace to an ADR (or won't be one) is a signal to slow down.

## Alternatives considered

- **Wiki / Notion / Confluence** — rejected because decisions drift away from
  the code; no PR-time review.
- **Inline comments / commit messages** — rejected because they don't surface
  in the right places when someone needs to understand the system.
- **No formal record** — rejected because we already lived this and forgot why.

## Verification

- This file exists.
- New decisions arrive as `docs/adr/NNNN-*.md` files (auto-created
  during plan close-out, or written manually).
- The index in `docs/adr/README.md` lists every ADR with its current status.
